<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2010 GMT, August 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudanese President Omar Hassan al-Bashir said
Friday that the Sudan will not submit to the U.S. tyrannical
force, calling on the Sudanese people to reject the U.S. hegemony.
</P>
<P>
Bashir made the remarks at a news conference held here following
an emergency session of the Sudanese National Security and Defense
Council to discuss the Thursday bombing of a Sudanese factory by
U.S. warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Bashir strongly denounced the U.S. Administration and described
it as ignorant and incapable of defining the sites it was after.
</P>
<P>
He further reiterated that the Sudan maintained the right to
respond to the U.S. aggression. (BC-Sudan-US Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudan decided Friday to recall its diplomats in
Washington to protest the U.S. air raid on a pharmaceutical
factory in Khartoum Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After a cabinet meeting chaired by al-Bashir, Minister of
Culture and Information Ghazi Saleh el-Din said the government has
also decided to file compliants with the United Nations, the Arab
League and other international organizations over the U.S. attack.
</P>
<P>
The country's International Civil Aviation Authority will
adopt measures to prevent U.S. aircrafts from flying over the
Sudanese airspace to preserve its national security, he said.
(BC-Sudan-US-Diplomats)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Arab League (AL) Friday condemned the United
States air raid on a Sudanese facility as "serious aggression
against a sovereign Arab country."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, the AL General Secretariat
expressed "shock and resentment" at the U.S. attack Thursday night
on a pharmaceutical plant in Sudan's capital Khartoum, which
injured several civilians.
</P>
<P>
The 22-member AL accused the U.S. of flagrantly violating
international laws and conventions and the United Nations
Charter. (BC-Arab League-US-Condemnation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Foreign Ministry said Friday Turkey strongly
supports the United States' air strikes against the "terrorist
bases" in Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, the ministry said that Turkey
condemns all kinds of terrorism whatever its sources or purposes,
and is one of the main supporters of the international cooperation
in the struggle against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey strongly supports the bilateral and international
cooperation agreements against terrorism," it said. (BC-Turkey-US
Raids-Support)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt renewed a call Friday for holding a world summit
to discuss fighting terrorism in a collective and organized way,
the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In response to Thursday's U.S. air raids on suspected terrorist
bases in Sudan and Afghanistan, Egypt called on the United Nations
to host a world summit on combating terrorism.
</P>
<P>
It urged the U.N. Security Council to take appropriate measures
in line with the U.N. Charter to fight and root out terrorism and
bring those responsible to justice. (BC-Egypt-Terrorism-World
Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran Friday condemned the United States for its
attack on Sudan Thursday, terming it as a move violating Sudan's
sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Tehran radio quoted the Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud
Mohammadi as saying that the U.S. raid on a Sudanese factory was a
measure against the Sudanese people and "we condemn it."
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi stated that Iran always condemns terrorists. However,
he said, no event could be used as a pretext for the U.S. to do
what it likes and to attack the Islamic lands.
(BC-Iran-Condemnation-US Attacks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel has expressed its support for the
U.S. strike on "terrorist-related" bases in Afghanistan and
Sudan, saying it stood by Washington in its fight against
international terrorism, Israel Radio reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his office late Thursday night,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu praised the
U.S. "particularly for choosing to hit the terror infrastructure
and terrorist bases in Sudan and Afghanistan," the radio said.
(BC-Israel-US-Strike) 
</P>
